	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2754867940" id="dsq-comment-2754867940">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2754867940">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-06-28</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2754867940" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2754867940" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Those two behaviors specifically will be very difficult to get working together. And it kind of makes sense - versioning is already hard in a relational database (you need to duplicate each row before it's changed). Add onto that the fact that each row now has many translations, and you quickly (and correctly) get a big, ugly matrix. I use some of the more magic behaviors sparingly - learning from Doctrine version 1 that the magic has costs. For example, on our apps, we don't use Loggable/versionable or soft deletable.</p><p>So, my best advice is to consider doing *less* - these behaviors try to make a relational database do things that it doesn't naturally do well. If you layer on too many, I don't think you'll be happy.</p><p>Cheers!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
